<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-08-25T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-08-25T08:00:00-05:00" n="149" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d149">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">822.00/793: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ecuador</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Dawson</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Quito</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-08-25T08:00:00-05:00">August 25, 1931—8
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 11:36 a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>39. Colonel Larrea Alba appears to have the situation well in hand and
                            the support of the entire Army. Evidences of popular feeling against him
                            decreased visibly toward evening and the night passed quietly. Quito is
                            quiet this morning and the Legation has no reports of disorders
                            elsewhere.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Dawson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>